<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910919-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910919-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing Brief -- Canadian Satellite:   Application Made to Launch   Its Own Satellite in 1995</HL><DATE>09/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10</SO><CO>   T.SAT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   Canadian Satellite Communications Inc. applied to theCanadian government for permission to launch its ownsatellite in 1995 to distribute radio and television signalsacross Canada.   The company currently transmits radio and TV signals viathe satellite system of Telesat Canada, which is the onlycompany authorized to own and operate communicationssatellites in Canada. Telesat is jointly owned by theCanadian government and by telephone companies and othercommon communications carriers.</LP><TEXT>   Canadian Satellite Communications said it proposes tolaunch a &quot;lightsat&quot; type satellite. Such satellites aresmaller and lighter than conventional communicationssatellites.   A Telesat spokesman questioned the feasibility of theproposed venture. He said Canadian Satellite Communicationswas asking to use an orbital position that Telesat currentlyoccupies and has no intention of giving up.</TEXT></DOC>